---

Main Outcome

The regularity correction remains strongly effective at the million scale.

Improvements:

Top 10 primes: 3 -> 8

Top 20 primes: 7 -> 15

Mean prime rank: 372.110345 -> 341.558621

Mean non-prime rank: 406.328244 -> 413.091603


This means:

the top of the ranking became much cleaner

the average prime moved upward substantially

the average non-prime moved downward

the correction still works under lower natural prime density



---

The Critical Case: 1,000,001

1,000,001 is the strongest validation object in this run.

Observed behavior:

raw_rank = 2

adj_rank = 112

pen_norm = 1.0000


Interpretation:

1,000,001 is an extreme symbolic regularity trap. Raw OMNIA treated it as one of the best candidates in the entire interval. The regularity penalty identified it as maximally suspicious and removed it from the hot zone.

This is the million-scale analogue of the earlier 30031 result.


---

Tracked Prime Movement

Several legitimate primes rose sharply after the correction:

1000003: 14 -> 4

1000033: 42 -> 18

1000037: 9 -> 3

1000039: 11 -> 5

1001993: 5 -> 1

1001999: 28 -> 12


Interpretation:

The correction does not only suppress bad composites. It also clears structural noise and allows legitimate primes to emerge more clearly.


---

Minimal Valid Claim

This run supports the following narrow claim:

The regularity correction with λ = 0.03 generalizes successfully to the million scale.

More precisely:

top-ranked prime concentration improves very strongly

mean-rank separation improves

high-regularity composite traps are sharply de-ranked

legitimate primes gain visibility



---

What This Does Not Yet Prove

This run does not yet prove that:

the correction is universally valid at all scales

λ = 0.03 is globally optimal

the adjusted system is close to a primality test

all remaining false positives are explained


It shows only that the correction remains effective under a significantly harder regime.


---

Final Compression

At the million scale, raw OMNIA still sees signal, but the adjusted version is clearly better.

The regularity correction:

cleans the top of the ranking

suppresses major composite traps

improves mean-rank separation

remains effective under lower prime density


This is the strongest post-hoc validation result obtained so far.

